ional emphasis on individual interests such as doctor-patient relationships, informed consent, and personal autonomy is minimally helpful in confronting the social and political challenges posed by new human biotechnologies such as assisted reproduction, human genetic modification, and DNA forensics. Beyond Bioethics addresses these provocative issues from an emerging standpoint that is attentive to race, gender, class, disability, privacy, and notions of democracy—a ";new biopolitics."; This authoritative volume provides an overview for those grappling with the profound dilemmas posed by these developments. It brings together the work of cutting-edge thinkers from diverse fields of study and public engagement, all of them committed to this new perspective grounded in social justice and public interest values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBioethics. 0aBiopoliticszUnited States. 0aBiopolitics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamerican race laws.  aassisted reproduction.  abioethical sciences.  abioethics.  abiopolitical critique of bioethics.  abiopolitics.  abiotechnologies.  aconstructing normalcy.  acritical race studies.  adesigner babies.  adisability and bioethics.  adisability studies.  adna and ethics.  aeugenics.  afuture of medicine.  agenetic marketing.  agenetic modification.  ahuman biotechnologies.  aivf and eugenics.  amedical exploitation.  anazis and american race laws.  arace and bioethics.  astudy of bioethics.  ayuppie eugenics.1 aAngell, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsch, Adrienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAthanasiou, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyeh, Derek, econtributor.4ctb